      <div class="col-lg-9 " id="2A ">
        <div class="panel panel-info ">
          <div class="panel-heading " style="text-align:center; ">
            <h4>
              <a> A. General Provisions</a>
            </h4>
          </div>
          <div class="panel-body ">
            <ul>
              <li>“Good Discipline” refers to the desired and expected norms of conduct of every SUNBEAMER. It involves helping
                children learn right from wrong by providing logical consequences for appropriate and inappropriate behaviors.
                As provided by Education Act of 1982 section 15, the following are the Duties and Responsibilities of Students:</li>
              <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; ">
                <li>Exerts his outmost to develop his potentialities for service, particularly by undergoing an education suited
                  to his abilities, in order that he may become an asset to his family and society.</li>
                <li>Uphold the academic integrity of the school endeavor to achieve academic excellence and abide the rules and
                  regulations governing his academic responsibilities and moral integrity.</li>
                <li>Promote and maintain the peace and tranquility of the school by observing the rules and discipline, and by
                  exerting efforts to attain harmonious relationships with fellow students, the teaching and academic staff
                  and other school personnel.</li>
                <li>Participate actively in civic affairs and in the promotion of the general welfare, particularly in the social,
                  economic and cultural development of his community and in the attainment of a just, compassionate and orderly
                  society.
                </li>
                <li>Exercise his rights responsibly in the knowledge that he is answerable for any infringement or violation
                  of the public welfare and of the rights of others.</li>
              </ol>
              <li>Authority means the power to enforce law, exact obedience and command. Executive Order No. 209 other known
                as THE FAMILY CODE OF THE PHILIPPINES Art. 218 provide that, “The school, its administrators and teachers,
                or the individual, entity or institution engaged in child care shall have special parental authority and
                responsibility over the minor child while under their supervision, instruction or custody. Authority and
                responsibility shall apply to all authorized activities whether inside or outside the premises of the school,
                entity or institution.”</li>
              <li>School administrators, teachers and personnel are entrusted to enforce and maintain discipline as persons of
                authority; however, the parents and guardians must realize that they have a social and moral obligation to
                assist and cooperate with school authorities to foster order and discipline.</li>
            </ul>

          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-3 " id="myScrollspy ">

      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-9 " id="2B ">
        <div class="panel panel-info ">
          <div class="panel-heading " style="text-align:center; ">
            <h4>
              <a> B. Categories of Administrative Penalties </a>
            </h4>
          </div>
          <div class="panel-body ">
            <p>The following administrative penalties shall be applied upon pupils and students who incur infractions of school
              rules and regulations and after proper investigation by school authorities:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Suspension – the child is denied attendance of classes for a period not exceeding 20% of the number of school
                days. No make-up work or special tests shall be provided. There are two kinds of suspension:</li>
              <ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; ">
                <li>Punitive – the child is required to report to school for detention or performance of community service under
                  the supervision of the Prefect of Discipline.</li>
                <li>Preventive – the child cannot be allowed to enter the campus, such as when the school believes that his/her
                  attendance may result in disruption of school operations or pose a risk to any person in school. At such
                  case, the child shall be under the supervision of the parent/guardian.</li>
              </ol>
              <li>Exclusion - wherein the child is dropped from enrollment and the school issues transfer credentials immediately.
                This shall be the result of a summary investigation and need not require approval of the Department of Education.</li>
              <li>Expulsion - an extreme penalty wherein the child is prevented from admission to any private or public school
                in the Philippines and requires the approval of the Department of Education.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-3 " id="myScrollspy ">

      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-9 " id="2C ">
        <div class="panel panel-info ">
          <div class="panel-heading " style="text-align:center; ">
            <h4>
              <a> C. Due Process </a>
            </h4>
          </div>
          <div class="panel-body ">
            <ul>
              <li>It is the prerogative of the school to issue warnings to pupils and student who break rules and regulations;
                however, gross or habitual infractions shall result in immediate disciplinary action.</li>
              <li>Disciplinary action shall be taken only after a proper investigation of the case has been conducted by the
                Principal/Department Head in consultation with the Class Adviser and School Director and the knowledge of
                the parent/guardian. Thus, parents and guardians must come immediately to school if summoned for discussion
                of the results of the investigation.</li>
              <li>In case of exclusion, the case shall be filed by the Guidance Counselor for one school year to afford the Department
                of Education the opportunity to review the case and respond to amy appeals.</li>
              <li>Cases involving expulsion shall be referred to the Department of Education Regional Office ten days after termination
                of the investigation.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
